title: ANET A8 Nozzle Filament Wiper - Cleaner

description.text:
So I've been thinking of creating a way of reliably cleaning my extruder's nozzle for sometime. Well this works well for me. It used the rubber part from a car window screen wiper. I've looked at 3 different types (cheap ones), and they all seem to have the same profile, so hopefully yours will fit.

https://youtu.be/Y2JuGVRIpto

Slide the rubber into the tapered end of the 3D printed part. Attach the part to the lower section (non-heated) of your heated bed, just by pushing it on (no screws required!). Your G-Code may need some adjustment, but the code below just moved the head to the front of the wiper, moves back slowly to clean it, lifts up, and moves to do it again. It does this 3 times, then just moves away to continue as normal.

The video isn't that clear, but hopefully gives you an idea what is going on.

; * Cleaning Code ***
G1 X185 F4000
G1 Y-13 F4000
G1 Z1
G1 E3 F100; PURGE NOZZLE
G1 Y0 F100
G1 Z8 F200
G1 Y-13 F4000
G1 X191
G1 Z1 F100
G1 Y0 F100
G1 Z8 F200
G1 Y-13 F4000
G1 X196
G1 Z1 F100
G1 Y0 F100
G1 Z8 F200
; *****

description.text:
I printed off JustinSDK's version and it was really neat, but I hated poking myself while holding it. I mean it is a cube with sharp edges and tossing it back in forth while at my desk wore on me!

So I made a softer touch version. I hope people enjoy. You get the same great effect, and a slightly cooler appearance (in my opinion), that you can also play with.

I also made the holder 135% for the box's current size. This seemed to fit better, or more securely.

UPDATE 2016-03-24 I totally reworked the resource tray, with a fully adjustable SolidPython/OpenSCAD design. The .stl file has ~0.7mm margin in both x- and -y direction for each card slot, and 50mm sleeve height (the 91 mm high cards slide 50 mm into each slot. And there's a 30mm height difference between the two levels. These are all adjustable parameters in the script. I also added STLs for most expansions (cards only, you must store tokens and mats separately) NOTE: If you aren't sure about your printer calibration, scale the z-axis down to 1/5th size (but leave X- and Y-axes alone) to do a test print. Test the slot sizes with your actual cards. All printers are different, and you'll probably have to scale both X- and Y- to get the right fit. Or if you are on linux, you can download the python script and re-run it with a new calibration file (caldata.py) or with a different margin values.

Dominion is a great game, but always lots of counting and sorting of cards, and making space to lay out all the piles. After calibrating my printer, I was able to make perfect-sized slots. The cards are snug, but still easy to insert or remove. For reference, this holds exactly:
  • 60 copper
  • 40 silver
  • 30 gold
  • 12 platinum (or something else, if not using Prosperity)
  • 24 estates
  • 12 duchies
  • 12 provinces
  • 12 colonies (or something else, if not using Prosperity)
  • 30 curses
    • Earlier versions of dominion came with more duchies and estates. The script should be smart enough to adapt if you change the card counts near the top (for instance, if you really want to hold 30 estates instead of 24)

You can probably just skip the math below, and make a test print rescaling the Z-axis to about 20%.  Try inserting the cards into the short slots, and adjusting the X- and Y-scaling, before doing a full print.  Doing this full print with 1 shell, 10% infill, at 100mm/s and 0.3mm layer height, took about 7 hours.  It is 144g, which is like $5 worth of PLA.  So get the sizes right before committing to the full print!

You may consider calibrating your printer first:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:230596
The most important thing is the slot sizes: measure the inner widths in the x- and y-axes, to see how much error you have. In my case, if I specify a slot of width X and Y, my print has a slot of size X0.935-0.25, and Y0.94-0.6. So I added .25mm to the X-slot sizes and 0.6mm to the Y-slot sizes, and then an extra 0.5mm to each for "margin". That is how the model was made. That compensates for the width of 1 shell on an MBot Cube 2, but doesn't include the rescaling.
Then before slicing, I scaled the X-axis by 107%, and the Y-axis by 106.4% in Makerware. Doing this, I got a perfect fit.
FYI:  A dominion card is exactly 91mm x 59mm x 0.3mm

title: Printable Gauge to set the plate - for Prusa Mendel

description.text: Use two of the indicators to quickly and easily set the Plate in the level.   The tilt of indicator of 1 mm corresponds to the height of 0.17 mm. With ease you set the height to an accuracy of 0.08 mm.

You will need two level indicators.
1) Print two.
2) Assemble the arms. Use two nuts on each screw.
Warning: The lower arm (arrow) has slightly and freely move. Both indicators must show exactly the same value.
They must be calibrated. Install one at any point on the X axis.
Set X-axis height so that the arms indicator are parallel.
White pen mark level of the arm and remove it from the X axis.
Then, without changing anything, the second indicator mount exactly the same place. Mark level of the arm and remove it from the X axis.
Ok, now both indicators show the same height.
  • Leveling plate -
    Install both indicators at the opposite ends X axis.
    Move the Y axis, check the height at the corners of the Plate.
    Et voilÃ , allez! ;-)

title: X carriage mounted extruder filament guide

description.text: This assembly bolts up to the stock extruder mounting holes on the Reach 3D printer. The holes in the Mounting Bracket are sized to be tapped. There are 3 M3 holes for mounting to the printer and 1 M4 hole for assembling the unit. The fasteners required are 3 M3 x 8mm to mount the unit and 1 M4 x 20mm to hold the assembly together. A 20mm OD x 8mm ID bearing gets pressed into the middle of the guide wheel. Slide the bearing cap onto the M4 screw, then slide the guide wheel onto the bearing cap. Next slide the bearing mount onto the M4 screw and thread the screw into the mounting bracket. Make sure the bearing mount is pointing down and to the back of the Z axis column. Finally insert a length of PTFE tube into the bearing mount to go from your spool to the guide to keep your filament from touching your work surface an picking up dirt.

description.text:
My family got one of those widely available 4 Tier Mini Greenhouse kits this spring. It's pretty handy, but a pain to move to shelter when severe weather is incoming. I thought a set of 4" swivel casters would be just the thing. I got ones with a 1/2" x 1-1/2" threaded stem, but ran into two problems. The threaded stem turned out to have a little bit too much play in the greenhouse bracket holes and the stem is offset from the axle by 1-1/4", putting the whole thing at risk of tipping over when moved around. That's where these adapters come in, taking care of both the fit and the offset.

Two cautions if you print and use these:

  1. The radius on the upper edge of the greenhouse bracket plug is not exactly right, so don't use excessive force inserting it. I gave them a few whacks with a rubber mallet and can see stress marks in the plastic of the greenhouse brackets where that edge is.
  2. These adapters are sturdier than the greenhouse itself, so there is a chance that the offset will allow the greenhouse brackets to twist and break under a heavy load. The brackets where these are inserted may require reinforcement for safety. I won't get a chance to see how these perform under full load until next year.

title: Dual Extrude Both Extruders at Once for Replicator

description.text:
This is a script and instructions on how to run both extruders at the same time to get two objects printed at once.  
This may have been the starting point for ditto printing on dual extruder MakerBots, but it has probably been superceded by the ditto function in Sailfish Firmware.

How it Works
-the script basically changes every extruder movement for 1 extruder ( an E000) to an extruder control movement for both extruders (A000 B000). Dimension/5D has to be enabled for this to work.
Work Flow
-Generate gCode as per usual but use start.gcode with Dimension based Anchor
-Run the generated Gcode thru the script
-open the gcode with ReplicatorG and print
Settings that need to be changed
-dimension needs to be turned on in Skeinforge so the we get an E000 code
for extruder movements.
-the ReplicatorG34/machines/Replicator.xml file needs to be changed so the maxfeedrate on A and B is 4600 instead of 1600 so skeinforge does not throw a fit everytime you generate gcode. I arbitrarily picked 4600- if someone knows the proper number let me know.
-in skeinforge alterations tab- remove Redundant Gcode needs to be unchecked otherwise the warmup of the 2nd extruder gets removed
-there are two version of the gcode conversion script- one for XP another for Vista and Win7- in the Win7 version you need to edit the script to change the file name that is being converted each time(if someone has a way to do a file dialog like the XP version let me know)
-you can either:
-use the dimension based start.gode all the time
-create profile that uses it the dimension based start.code
-use the "use default start/end.gcode" setting in the generate print dialog to control which one you use
-the startup gcode also has some warmup tricks I am currently testing. The bed seems to be the slow spot in the warmup so I turn it on at the start of the script. I don't wait for it to be warm at that point simply turn it on, I use 105 degrees in case it is already warm. Then once the homing is done. I wait for it to warm to 100 then turn it to 110 without waiting(I don't think the bed has to be at 110 before we start printing). Then the extruders get turned on and we wait for them to be ready.
Know Issues
-the anchor gcode of the startup-gcode need some work.
-Mac and Linux people are out of luck for the time being- the conversion code is pretty straight forward if someone wants to convert it
Thanks to Rob Giseburt for the advice on how to start the process.
Let me know if you find any issues.
You may also want to check out http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:24195 by JoeyC He made a derivative that is written in C.

1. Print it out

It took about 32 hours to print in this size on my printer.

2. Grinding and Putty

Used 240 sandpaper at start and finished with 1000.
Used stadard vall putty, probobly not the best for outdor but i will either epoxy or finishing with coat of varnish.

3. Wash with alcohol

Use iso-propanol to was away any grease and dust after grinding.

4. Spray primer

Used a white spray on bottle.

5. Airbrush background and face

I painted with the airbrush in a black background,
Don't do this beacuse it will be harder to cover that color then you paint with airbush in other colors later. Use white instead!

Then i airbrushed the face with my mix of beige and red.

You need to mask the head then airbrushing the cap.

9. Airbrush bottom plate

Surround Mario with plastic film as masking.
Then start airbrush the plate in a nice green color.

10. Finising painting
  • Add the "M" for mario
  • Add Eyes
  • Fixed legs that got sprayed with green.

11. Finishing coat of varnish

description.text:
This was inspired by how, in Mass Effect games, Commander Shepard shoves everything up his abyss when he's not using it. Although it would be difficult to make Nerf blasters that fold into such compact form factors automatically, we can still hold them on our backs, hips, anywhere, no matter how big they are.

This design is a holster for blasters that do not fit in a regular holster. At 50% scale it can hold a Retaliator in pistol form rather well. At 100% scale it can hold a heavily modded Longshot. At 150-200% scale, it can hold a homemade.

At 100% scale it uses 1 inch straps. Strap width changes proportionally with scale.

For horizontal-insert applications, I strongly recommend shimming the male side or using some other method to drastically increase hold.

I do not recommend printing this bigger than 200% or smaller than 50%.

description.text: This is a bracket that allows you to mount a 20mm pipe between the legs of a Lack table to act as a spool holder.

If you'd like to order one of these printed, they are available through my website: https://bit-district.com/console/sega-dreamcast/usb-gdrom-tray.html

The USB-GD-ROM Controller is a device that replaces the ever failing disc drives in Sega Dreamcast consoles. These are great devices but they leave a very large space open inside the console meaning you can easily, accidentally drop your USB Stick inside the console and it leave a big ugly open hole under the lid. This tray is designed to slide down on top of the USB port on the USB-GDROM device and seal off the inside of the console dramatically improving the loop with the lid open and making it impossible to drop your USB stick inside through an open lid.

I've also added an alternative "external" variant for those who have the older USB GD-ROMs with an External USB Port, this creates a simple storage pocket under the Dreamcast's lid to finish off the space.

description.text:
The tiny 40mm x 10mm fan inside the QiDi Tech 1 that allegedly cools the stepper motor driver modules is the noisiest thing in the entire printer. When you turn on the printer, that fan is what you hear whether you are printing anything or not. After a year, I got sick of listening to it and have replaced it with a 75mm x30mm low speed blower.

This printable part is the mounting bracket that you will need to hold the 75mm blower. It re-uses the 40mm fan's existing L-bracket metalwork and mounting screws.

Printer:

QiDi Tech 1

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.3

Notes:

PARTS NEEDED:
1 each: 75mm x 30mm low speed blower
https://www.digikey.com/product-detail/en/delta-electronics/BFB0724L/603-1569-ND
Note: This was the most quiet, 24VDC, blower type air mover that I could find.

2 each: M3 x 40mm length bolts with nuts

Update 6/18/17 - I've added a few pix of the installed fan and added to some of the installation text. I love how my printer is quiet now when I power it up. Definitely worth the effort to get rid of that noisemaker.

Update 6/22/17 - After dakahler made one of the mounts for the QiDi Tech 1 and got it to work in the QiDi X-One, I made a minor tweak to improve the fit when used in that printer. I've added a version that will work in either QiDi printer. NOTE: This dual-printer version has not yet been printed and confirmed to fit.

INSTALLATION INSTRUCTIONS:

Print out the new bracket and remove it from the printer. Move the print platform to the home position. Turn off the printer. Flip the printer onto its side and disconnect the power. Remove the screws holding the bottom plate.

In the next steps, the original L-bracket used to mount the 40mm fan is removed from the QiDi and will be reused in the same location and orientation. So take a picture if you have any doubts. Pop the two screws that hold the L-bracket in place from inside the printer (on the bottom of the print chamber surface beneath the print platform). The old fan and its L-bracket should now be loose. Remove the 40mm fan from the L-bracket (retain the two screws). Attach the L-bracket to the new blower bracket using the same two screws that had been used to hold the original fan. Note: The new blower bracket's mounting tab should be on the inside of the "L".

The blower is then attached to the opposite side of the blower bracket using two 40mm long M3 (or similar) screws and nuts. On my printer I also used a washer, a split washer and some locktite. (You will need to supply these screws and nuts / hardware.) Put the nuts on the bracket side of the assembly. When mounting the blower to the bracket, bear in mind that the blower air exit aperture should be positioned so as to cool the stepper driver modules. The blower's central air intake opening will face the underside of the printer.

Re-mount the completed new blower assy using the same two short screws that formerly held the L-bracket in place. When placing and affixing the new blower assembly, be careful not to stress the flat wire cable running from the front panel to the control board. I put some mastic foam tape on the new bracket's two standoff feet to avoid possible wear on the flat cable.

Trace the red/black wire pair from the old fan to the control board, and pop that corner connector from the control board. Wire the new fan in place of the old fan. Remove and re-connect the red (positive) lead first. Once the red lead re-connection is completed and tightened securely, then remove and re-connect the black wires.

Before replacing the bottom cover, CAREFULLY plug the printer back in and turn it on.
Confirm that the new fan is now turning and moving air onto the stepper modules, and that it is really quiet. (Grin!) Turn off the printer and disconnect power again. Replace the bottom cover, set the printer back upright, and plug it back in again.

You're done.

After the frame is glued together, glue three 3/8 washers into the recesses on one side of the frame. Then glue one 5/16 washer under each of the three 3/8 washers you just glued. Glue three more 3/8 washers into the recesses on the other side of the frame. You now have a complete spinner.

Next, print out the two (A & B) 26mm gem accessory. They are designed to fit together when pushed together through the holes in the washers. You may need to add a little glue to one side to secure these parts. Finally, glue in some acrylic jewels into the recesses in the gem accessory.

This is a simple mounting bracket for VanessaEzekowitz's B'Wadestruder to attach the extruder to 2020 extrusion in a different configuration than the original design. This is the Hooligan Flywheel Press and puller kit. The kit includes all the parts needed to build a press for pressing on all manner of nerf flywheels and removing them as well. The press will have multiple forks to work with many different styles of flywheel cages in time, but currently the Open Flywheel Project cage fork is available.

When printing, it is best to print the parts with threading WITHOUT support. They are oriented in the ideal position, and this will give a smoother threading. When threading parts together, it helps to add lubricant to the threads in the screw part. I rubbed an unused candle in the threads to help lubricate them, and found this solution offered a great lubricant while also preventing them from being messy. The first time threading will be tight either way, but as inperfections are smoothed, the fit becomes much easier.

The arms for he puller should be printed with support everywhere, These can be attached to the base with most common M3 nerf screws.

The "anvil" for the press will support the end bell of most motors and prevent then from being pushed out as the flywheels are pressed on. This grants a lot of control when adding flywheels and prevents damage to costly motors.

Videos will be added shortly to Demo these tools and explain there use. We will be working with other flywheel cage designers to make this tool as universal as possible.

These tools will be available at cost from the Hooligan Etsy store page.

description.text:
This allows for your 3D printer spools to be suspended directly above the extruder(s), and rotate horizontally to combat poor spooling (spiral effect) that is seen with some faulty filament rolls.

The problem:
I had a couple of rolls that were poorly spun that created a rigid spiral (or slinky effect) when printing. The issue seen from the worst spun rolls ended with failed prints due to the filament slinky effect being so bad as to wrap around printer parts, and jam the extruder feed motor. At one point, the filament roll was ripped from the holder, and dropped onto the machine with 3 hours left on a print.

The solution:
I created a suspended filament holder that utilizes a 608 bearing (same as in fidget spinners) to spin the roll to counteract any possible issues of badly spun rolls in the future. I used scrap 1/2-inch ID PVC piping, which is what the STL files fit.

Feel free to remix this!

Printer:

Prusa Clone

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

At least 30% for strength

Notes:

No rafts or support needed for the files. You can just print them outright.

The files are designed for standard 1/2-inch PVC piping. The piping should fit almost snug if you have your printer settings properly tuned in.

Main nut and bolt:
I used scrap from the garage. You can use any nut/bolt combination just as long as the bolt is at least 2 inches long, and fits easily within the inner part of the bearing. DO NOT tighten it snug to the perpendicular part. It should hang freely, and spin horizontally like a fidget spinner.

3D part connecting nuts and bolts:
Again, I used scrap hardware to put this together. 1-inch bolts were used for both the top and bottom. I designed the STL files to accommodate what I had on hand (i.e. the nut and bolt head size).

Tapping screws:
1/2-inch screws were used to hold the PVC piping in place, and give rigidity to the rig. I would strongly suggest drilling through the provided holes with a smaller drill bit to make sure these screws won't fracture the PVC piping.
Designed solely on TinkerCad.com.

Simple slide-on bracelet with triforce insert. It is scaled to fit my own wrist snugly (with my arm sticking straight in front of me and my palm facing down, my wrist is approximately 60mm from left to right and 45mm from top to bottom). You will probably need to scale the bracelet up or down to fit your wrist. Scale uniformly in all axis (to keep the triforce insert triangular), and don't forget to apply the same scale to the triforce. The triforce is designed to snap perfectly into insert (you may need to scale it up or down if your printer dimensions are a little off).

The bracelet should be printed at 0.2 layer height or lower with no infill (to give it some flex) and 2 shell perimeters (I used a 0.4 nozzle). The triforce should be printed at 0.1 layer height since it is slightly curved (to match bracelet curve), and I printed it at 100% infill. I printed this in Hatchbox wood PLA and some random unbranded orange/yellow PLA (see post-processing section below for wood stain)

Staining wood PLA

After printing in Hatchbox wood PLA, I used a "stain marker" to stain the bracelet (my particular stain marker is a dark walnut stain made by Rust-Oleum). Apply the stain marker in slow, uniform strokes (all strokes in the same direction and that direction should follow the layer lines). By slightly overlapping the strokes, it simulates wood grain and gives the wood a more realistic look. I do NOT sand the wood before staining, because in this particular application I think the layer lines enhance the wood look.

Note, the stain marker I used is 2-in-1 stain + finish (and it's instant dry)... so it doesn't rub off on my wrist and can get wet. If you use a different kind of stain, you may want to finish it with a protective coat so the stain doesn't rub onto your skin.

Update (2017/06/22):
CraftUnique recently released a PETG dome cover with an 80mm activated carbon filter for CraftBot Plus & CraftBot 2.

https://craftunique.com/item/craftbot2-petg-dome-cover

Below is my custom top enclosure for my CraftBot prior to CraftUnique's new dome cover, see above.

I purchased the 5-sided acrylic clear cube from MisterPlexi, part number is: AC14-16, a 14"W x 14"D x 14"H cube with the bottom open.

http://www.misterplexi.com/products/ac14-16.html

Just print out the box holders, screw them to the top of your CraftBot, put the box on it, load your filament from under in the back and you're ready to print.

Note: I have heard from other CraftBot users reported that with fully enclosed (based on other enclosure designs), the temperature inside may rise too high which may affect your print results or extruder/hotend, especially in a hot summer day.

So my design probably would face above similar issues. If that happens, then you may want to consider cutting a small opening on top to help keep the heat inside under better control.

I don't print large objects often so I don't have much issues so far. My main concern is to keep the ABS fume inside as much as possible. I can smell the fume but it's a lot less with the top enclosure on.

There are some minor gaps between the holder. So far it works adequately and meets my need, so I will no longer work on it anymore.

However, please feel free to modify it or come up with your own design. Enjoy!

http://www.michaels.com/pro-mag-neodymium-magnets-.5%22/10382640.html

I reprinted this in ABS. The PLA wasn't handling the heat well when I enclosed the printer.

I also decreased the bend angle slightly, giving the cable chain a slightly larger bend radius.

The top mount piece is also redesigned. Now it "hugs" the carriage and gets zip-tied on. There is a bit up play upwards, but is can't come off. Feed the zip ties through the holes in the bottom first these are to secure the wires. Getting the mount attached to the carriage is a bit tricky. There is a small curved hole to guide the zip tie around the bend. I took me a few tries to get the holes lined up and the zip tie fed through. I am open to improvement suggestions. description.text: 2 Hamster Slides for getting from one level to the next. Smooth enough for most hamsters to slide but also rough enough to climb.

The design itself is hardly worth discussing: a simple cylinder sized to fit in a 608 bearing. But the reason for it is a little interesting.

I noticed my printed spinner had a pronounced vibration at certain speeds. Using an ungreased ceramic bearing, it had a tendency to turn the same side down when held vertically. I weighed the mass bearings with a centigram scale ($14 on Amazon) and found that the heaviest one was nearly .3g more than the lightest one, or about 2.5% heavier.

I printed three of these at different infill settings, and after some trial and error was able to get the combined weight of bearing and weight to within .02 g. No more vibration.

The heaviest one at 100% infill comes out to .35g in PLA. The lightest one I printed with no infill and a single perimeter weighs .08g. If your weight difference is more than that, you may have to leave one out.

comments.text: I learned that if you print anything less than 100% infill on a spinner, it may have a balance issue. The infill patter doesn't care about weight per section and depending how that patter flopped down on the inside of your spinner, it could be pretty far off.
comments.author: almightykarl

comments.text: I always print spinners at 100%, just for the increased mass. Good point, though. I thought for a while it might be a balance issue due to uneven sanding, but an empty spinner didn't have a tendency to go one side low.
